{"cursor":"14176","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Ionbox\n| ImageFile1 = Nitrit-Ion2.svg ImageSize1 =170px ImageAlt1 = ImageFileL1 = Nitrite-3D-\n| vdW.png ImageSizeL1 = 121px ImageAltL1 = Space-filling model of the nitrite\n| ion ImageFileR1 = Nitriteion-resonance-hybrid.png ImageSizeR1 = 121px\n| SystematicName = Nitrite IUPACName = OtherNames = Section1 = {{Chembox\n| Identifiers CASNo = PubChem = SMILES = }} Section2 = {{Chembox Properties\n| Formula = MolarMass = 46.01 g mol -1 Appearance = Solubility = }}\n| Section3 = {{Chembox Hazards MainHazards = FlashPt = Autoignition = }}\n}}\n\nThe 'nitrite' ion, which has the chemical formula NO 2â , is\na symmetric anion with equal N-O bond lengths and a O-N-O bond angle of\napproximately 120Â°. Upon protonation, the unstable weak acid nitrous acid is\nproduced. Nitrite can be oxidized or reduced, with the product somewhat\ndependent on the oxidizing/reducing agent and its strength. The nitrite ion is\nan ambidentate ligand, and is known to bond to metal centers in at least five\ndifferent ways. Nitrite is also important in biochemistry as a\nsource of the potent vasodilator nitric oxide. In organic chemistry the\nNO 2 group is present in nitrous acid esters and nitro compounds.\nNitrites are also used in the food production industry for curing meat.\n","linknr":300,"url":"Nitrite","recorded":1362482423,"links":53,"instances":["food_preservation"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Nitrites|*","Oxoanions","Curing agents","Garde manger","Nitrogen metabolism"],"headings":["The nitrite ion","Organic nitrites and nitro compounds","See also","References","External links","Bibliography"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ec/Nitrit-Ion2.svg/170px-Nitrit-Ion2.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Nitrite-3D-vdW.png/121px-Nitrite-3D-vdW.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4a/Nitriteion-resonance-hybrid.png/121px-Nitriteion-resonance-hybrid.png","//